If it's a corporation they're shareholders, not partners.  I suppose it
would be possible for them to form a partnership that owns all the
shares, but that really wouldn't change anything.

In the case of a partnership or (in some states) a corporation, you
can't just "get rid" of one of the owners.  What you can do is to sue
to partition the property (business).  A court will order it sold to
the highest bidder.  If two of the "partners" get together and bid,
they can end up buying out the third if their price is the highest.

