<POST>
<POSTER> "Mike Jacobs" &lt;mjacobs...@gmail.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2006-10-26T08:13:00 </POSTDATE>
<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
David D wrote:
&gt; IF there are 3 parnters all owning 1/3 equally in a corporation - can
&gt; two band together to get rid of the third?  There are no shareholders
&gt; just the three partners.
">

First, this is the sort of thing that a prudent investor would be sure
is covered by a written agreement at the outset.   Nobody wants bad
things to happen, but the job of a lawyer drafting such an agreement is
to anticipate all the ways they might happen, and to provide a pre-set
and agreed path to be followed for each such contingency as part of the
deal.

Second, your terminology is confusing.   Corporations don't have
partners, they have shareholders, even if no fancy stock certificates
are issued and even if it is privately held.  Each person who owns a
share of the corporation is by definition a "shareholder."

A corporation is a separate legal entity from the individuals who own
it, a "fictive person", which must be created under the laws of a
particular sovereign and comply with that state's registration
requirements to even exist.   If a corporation does something wrong, it
is only the corporation, and not its shareholders, who can usually be
sued.    In order to even be created, a corporation needs written
"articles of incorporation" to be filed with a public records office
that spell out certain parameters of its existence, as well as written
"bylaws" governing its internal operation.   That would be the first
place to look.

A partnership, OTOH exists any time 2 or more persons get together for
a business venture, whether or not they spell out their rights and
duties vs. each other in writing, and whether or not it is intended to
be a permanent bond (like a marriage) or a one-time joint venture for a
particular project.   The general partners are all individually liable
for any debts or torts of the partnership.   If there is no written
partnership agreement, the law provides what will have to happen in the
event various situations occur.

So, was a separate legal entity created under the laws of your state,
or not?

If the venture you are talking about is simply an unwritten
partnership, it can be dissolved (in fact, technically it _is_
dissolved) at any time when one or more of the partners wants "out".
If the 2 remaining partners decide to continue in business together,
that is in effect a brand-new partnership involving just the 2 of them.
But the partnership assets and debts of the "old" partnership would
still have to be split equitably between the 3 former partners.

But you said this was a corporation, so you would have to look to the
rules set out in the corporation's organizing papers (articles of
incorp. and bylaws) as well as what the law requires, to answer your
question.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Is there a buy-out or someting that has to
&gt; happen?
">

Yes.  All other things being equal, the majority of shareholders
(owning 2/3 of the corporation) can force the other shareholder out of
managerial control but can't dissolve the minority owner's ownership
interest which is generally represented as a share of the ongoing
profit stream, which does have a calculable market value for sale
purposes.   The majority owners could buy out his interest but only if
he consents.   The only other way to force the minority owner to give
up all interest in the corporation is to dissolve the corporation.   In
that case, the old corporation would cease to exist, and the corporate
assets would have to be fairly split among the shareholders, after
paying off all corporate debts, same as with a partnership.

Obviously, nothing anybody says here is going to be of much direct use
to you since your terms are mixed up.   So, before doing anything rash,
do consult a local lawyer who can get all the facts and review all the
documents and advise you accordingly, if this is a real situation
happening to you.  Good luck,

