<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
David D &lt;netr ... @yahoo.com&gt; wrote:
&gt;IF there are 3 parnters all owning 1/3 equally in a corporation - can
&gt;two band together to get rid of the third?  There are no shareholders
&gt;just the three partners.  Is there a buy-out or someting that has to
&gt;happen?
">

You seem to have some confusion between a partnership and a
corporation.  A corporation _always_ has stock, although it is
possible for all the stock to be owned by one person -- as was the
case with my father's business in the 1970s.  A partnership never has
stock.

So, let's address the possibilities:

1. The business is a corporation, equally owned by 3 people (_not_
partners).  Each owns 1/3 of the shares.  Those shares can be sold,
although there may be a "shareholder's agreement" restricting who they
can be sold to.  That's fairly common for small and/or closely-held
corporations: the shareholders can sell only to each other, and the
agreement specifies the method for determining the "fair" price to be
paid.  In my experience, this will not be favorable to the person who
"wants out".

OTOH, if two stockholders want to be rid of the remaining one, they
would have to form a new corporation, sell the business to it at a
fair price, and then distribute the value equally among the three
shareholders.  If they try to sell it at below market value, the third
shareholder can ask a court to intervene to protect his interest, and
or sue for "breach of fiduciary duty" -- the management of a
corporation has a duty to operate the corporation for the benefit of the
shareholders, which in practice means maximizing the value of their
shares.

2. The business is a partnership.  Any(*) partner or partners can demand
dissolution of the partnership and distribution of the net assets
(what's left after paying the debts).  If two partners want to be rid
of the third, they can either go to court for a formal dissolution
(expensive), or reach an agreement with the third partner on a fair
price for his "share" of the partnership, then continue the business
as a two-person partnership.  If they can't agree on a price, they
will have to got to court, which costs money.  And it can be hard to
keep the business operating while busy in court, not to mention that
the court may have no option but to dissolve the business in order to
determine the "fair" price.  That will probably be lower than an equal
share of the running business, and it may be possible for the
remaining partners to get the business back in operation again, but
it's not a sure thing.

(*) This assumes a general partnership.  In a "limited" partnership, I
think only the general partner(s) can dissolve the partnership, but
the limited partners are still entitled to be bought out if the
general partner wants to be rid of (some of) them.
